02:00:06.420 --> 02:00:09.200
exactly would you describe the emotional

02:00:09.200 --> 02:00:13.800
impact of this being at first it was a

02:00:13.800 --> 02:00:17.820
relief because when he called me and i

02:00:17.820 --> 02:00:19.680
saw it i thought it was an emergency

02:00:19.680 --> 02:00:22.120
that we would have to intubate go into

02:00:22.120 --> 02:00:25.180
surgery when i saw that everything was

02:00:25.180 --> 02:00:30.860
worked out i felt at ease after that

02:00:30.860 --> 02:00:33.240
a surprise because you see something

02:00:33.240 --> 02:00:36.240
different different being

02:00:36.240 --> 02:00:39.680
then you start thinking like a doctor

02:00:39.680 --> 02:00:42.800
again could there be anything else could

02:00:42.800 --> 02:00:46.820
there be bleeding somewhere there weren't

02:00:46.820 --> 02:00:48.480
that many monitors so you just keep

02:00:48.480 --> 02:00:53.040
looking then you start analyzing then you

02:00:53.040 --> 02:00:56.100
calm down again and then looking at him you

02:00:56.100 --> 02:01:10.480
you start to get emotional because you begin to see not so much the physical aspect but the emotional aspect the aspect of consciousness you start to analyze other things

02:01:10.480 --> 02:01:28.860
consciousness mood whether he has the initiative to do things whether he's mobilizing himself whether he's afraid you see other things and as i said again it's the look that moves me a tranquil calm look i understand everything i appreciate what you've done here but it's time to go

02:01:28.860 --> 02:01:31.860
it's time to go

02:01:31.860 --> 02:01:35.860
let's go enough is enough he would even look up to the sky to get his bearings

02:01:35.860 --> 02:01:41.860
because there's a window there without bars or anything you could see it perfectly

02:01:41.860 --> 02:01:57.860
why do you why do you cry when you recollect the experience and what emotion comes up inside of you when you when you just when you think about it because nowadays doctors are criticized for everything they do

02:01:57.860 --> 02:02:15.860
the colleague i mentioned max vinisius once we operated on a child and when i went to talk to the mother she started scolding me and he interrupted her saying ma'am he's the surgeon not the person that ran your child over

02:02:15.860 --> 02:02:43.860
he did the surgery so when someone recognizes your work it's really great because our technical work is difficult it requires training but the hardest part for us doctors is enduring everything we see there's a quote from a famous gentleman from brazil called chico xavier where he says what you tolerate is just as important as what you know

02:02:43.860 --> 02:03:13.840
so you can see that it's a form of recognition it was a being who understood that i was doing my best despite being limited it was the best i could do i was giving my soul everything i could do was being done for him and for me who was saying forgive me for anything but everything we know how to do is being done for you it really is moving it feels like you're still

02:03:13.840 --> 02:03:29.840
stuck in that room and can never leave like a little piece of us stays there you leave the robot leaves a little piece of yourself stays there you go back there you know how did marcos venesis say that it affected him

02:03:29.840 --> 02:03:42.340
oh a lot he even began smoking more he'd smoke all day i would argue with him and my wife would say stop arguing with him

02:03:42.340 --> 02:03:47.440
i'd go in the bathroom and see a bunch of cigarette butts on the floor

02:03:47.440 --> 02:03:55.120
marcos venesis smoking you're smoking no no it's not me it's my wife his wife didn't smoke

02:03:55.120 --> 02:04:02.660
sylvana would say stop fighting with him so he took up smoking because of this experience with the

02:04:02.660 --> 02:04:06.580
being was did it cause him stress no he already smoked but then he started chain smoking

02:04:06.580 --> 02:04:10.080
one after the other

02:04:10.080 --> 02:04:14.740
why do you think the experience accelerated his smoking

02:04:14.740 --> 02:04:18.480
high level of stress you know really high level

02:04:18.480 --> 02:04:27.080
stress you see being a doctor is stressful isn't it because wherever you go you're a doctor

02:04:27.080 --> 02:04:31.940
if you crash your car you're a doctor if you insulted someone you're a doctor if you did this

02:04:31.940 --> 02:04:33.340
you're a doctor right doc

02:04:33.340 --> 02:04:37.800
so our lives aren't as simple as people say

02:04:37.800 --> 02:04:43.260
we don't earn as much as people say our mental work is immense

02:04:43.260 --> 02:04:47.420
you have to be polite even when you're tired

02:04:47.420 --> 02:04:52.080
you have to you know you have to answer even when you're busy

02:04:52.080 --> 02:04:57.900
the work of a doctor here in the united states you have a wonderful medicine

02:04:57.900 --> 02:05:01.040
but the work of a doctor on the front lines

02:05:01.040 --> 02:05:03.660
the young doctor is tough

02:05:03.660 --> 02:05:06.900
you have to learn you have to see

02:05:06.900 --> 02:05:10.240
there are endless meetings many sleepless nights

02:05:10.240 --> 02:05:14.400
so going back to the question you asked me when he looked at us

